<br>
Even if we could find a way to accelerate up to 99% of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>c</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> we'd incur time dilation, which is really not all that great of a thing. Sure, the biological clocks of the pilot and crew will slow tremendously (or stop if they reach <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>c</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->), but the universe around does not. You can take a 2 week trip to a distant star and come home 40,000 years later to a desolate wasteland of a planet. Tens of thousands of years of political advancements and strife, technological advancements, and evolution have zipped by in 2 weeks for you. There's no way you could catch up. <br>
<br>
On top of that, considering the size of our galaxy alone, traveling at near-light speeds would still take us hundreds of millions of years to get from anywhere to somewhere else.<br>
<br>
There are so many problems with this type of solution. The answer not in relativistic velocities and time dilation.   <p><br>
